body.p:
We start with
          \begin{align*}@x + 1 &= 3 \quad (\text{@subtracting } 1 \text{ @frombothsides}) \\
            @x &= 2.\end{align*}

Then, we look at 
          \begin{align*}- \left(@x + 1 \right) &= 3 \quad (\text{@distributingtheparentheses})\\
            - @x - 1 &= 3 \quad (\text{@adding } 1 \text{ @tobothsides})\\
            - @x &= 4 \quad (\text{@dividingbothsidesby} -1)\\
              @x &= - 4.\end{align*}

In this example, $\vert @x + 1 \vert = 3$, we need to solve two 
      equations:
      \begin{align*}@x + 1 = 3\end{align*}
        and
      \begin{align*}@x + 1 = -3.\end{align*}

answer.p:
Either
            \begin{align*}@x = 22\end{align*}
          or
            \begin{align*}@x = -22\end{align*}

Recalling our definition of the absolute value function, we can solve this equation
          using piecewise notation:
          \begin{align*}\vert @x + 4 \vert 
            = \begin{nagwaCases}@x + 4 & \text{@if } @x \geq -4,\\
            - \left(@x + 4 \right) & \text{@if } @x < -4.\end{nagwaCases}\end{align*}

When $@x < -4$, we need to solve the equation
          \begin{align*}\frac{11 @x + 44}{- \left(@x + 4 \right)} 
            &= @x \quad (\text{@multiplyingbothsidesby } - \left(@x + 4 \right))\\
            11 @x + 44 &= - @x \left(@x + 4 \right) \quad (\text{@distributingtheparentheses})\\
            11 @x + 44 &= - @x^2 - 4 @x \quad (\text{@adding } @x^2 \text{ @and } 4 @x \text{ @tobothsides})\\
            @x^2 + 15 @x + 44 &= 0 \quad (\text{@factoringthelefthandside})\\
            \left(@x + 11 \right) \left(@x + 4 \right) &=  0.\end{align*}

Finally, when $@x > 3$, we know that $@x - 3 > 0$
          and $@x + 1 > 0$. We need to solve the equation
          \begin{align*}\left(@x - 3 \right) - \left(@x + 1 \right) &= 4\\
          @x - 3 - @x - 1 &= 4\\
          -4 &= 4.\end{align*}

Either
            \begin{align*}4 @x &= 0 \quad (\text{@dividingbothsidesby } 4)\\
          @x &= 0\end{align*}
          or
            \begin{align*}\vert @x \vert - 1 &= 0 \quad (\text{@adding } 1 \text{ @tobothsides})\\
              \vert @x \vert &= 1.\end{align*}

Either
            \begin{align*}@x = 1\end{align*}
          or
            \begin{align*}@x = -1.\end{align*}

So,
              \begin{align*}\text{@either } @x 
                = 11 \quad \text{@or} \quad @x = 1.\end{align*}

LHS:
            \begin{align*}\sqrt{4 \left(\textcolor{Red}{11} \right)^2 
              - 28 \left(\textcolor{Red}{11} \right) + 49}
              = \sqrt{225} = 15\end{align*}
          RHS:
            \begin{align*}\vert \left(\textcolor{Red}{11} \right) + 4 \vert 
              = \vert 15 \vert = 15\end{align*}
          and

LHS:
            \begin{align*}\sqrt{4 \left(\textcolor{Red}{1} \right)^2 
              - 28 \left(\textcolor{Red}{1} \right) + 49}
              = \sqrt{25} = 5\end{align*}
            RHS:
            \begin{align*}\vert \left(\textcolor{Red}{1} \right) + 4 \vert 
              = \vert 5 \vert = 5.\end{align*}

In the first scenario, we solve the equation
            \begin{align*}@x^2 + 13 @x + 21 
              &= 21 \quad (\text{@subtracting } 21 \text{ @frombothsides})\\
              @x^2 + 13 @x 
              &=  0 \quad (\text{@factoringthelefthandside})\\
              @x \left(@x + 13 \right) 
              &= 0.\end{align*}
